De novo transcriptome analysis of the oleaginous Scenedesmus acutes TRISTR8540. was performed in order to generate a reference transcriptome for gene discovery and metabolic pathway reconstitution. RNA were extracted from cells cultivated in Tris-acetate medium with or without nitrogen source. Illumina RNA-seq strategy was used to obtain approximately 16G data of pair-endx100bp reads. De novo transcriptome was generated using Trinity software. Annotation was performed by Blast2GO.

We aimed to create a de novo reference transcriptome of A. falcatus grown in batch culture. This assembly is valuable for researchers who need to parse apart genes that belong to zooplankton versus their algal food resource. A. falcatus is a member of many freshwater communities, so the reference transcriptome will also benefit metatranscriptomic analyses of freshwater phytoplankton diversity. Additionally, this assembly will be useful as a reference transcriptome for any other studies that require such molecular ecology resources.

Microalgae can effectively accumulate starch by nutritional limitation methods for bioalcohol fuel production. However, relatively little studies focused on the starch accumulation in microalgae and its molecular basis, especially under sulfur limitation condition. In this study, the starch accumulation kinetics and physiological responses of Chlorella sorokiniana under sulfur starvation (SS) and sulfur replenishment (SR) conditions were investigated, and factors involved in the transcriptional regulation were explored.

Nitrogen (N)-deprivation plays important role for lipid accumulation in microalgae. Here we report the comparative physiological and genetic analyses of Chlorella sorokiniana strains from different environmental regions of arctic glacier (Chlorella-Arc), desert soil (Chlorella-Des) and temperate native lake (Chlorella-Nat) in response to N-deprivation, for screening the optimal strain for biodiesel production.

Industrial microalgal chlorella are able to process wastewater with great efficiency, for which the molecular base remains elusive, partially due the lack of genome information and poorly-established model organisms for research. In this study, we report three newly sequenced and assembled genomes of Chlorella, including Chlorella sorokiniana BD09, Chlorella sorokiniana BD08 and Chlorlella sp. Dachan, all of which are widely used in piggery industry for nutrient removal from the wastewater.

Chlorella species are among the most interesting microalgae for biomass and biofuel production because of the high productivity, high lipid content and resistance to high light conditions. Moreover, several Chlorella sp. can be cultivated in mixotrophy, adding a reduced carbon substrate as a source of energy in addition to the photosynthetic process. In this work, we investigated the molecular basis of autotrophic vs. mixotrophic growth of Chlorella sorokiniana UTEX1230 strain. In mixotrophic conditions we observed an enhanced biomass, proteins, lipids and starch productivity when compared to autotrophic conditions. Despite decreased chlorophyll and chlorophyll binding protein accumulation, photosynthetic properties were essentially unaffected in C. sorokiniana by acetate addition. Differential gene expression profile in autotrophy as compared to mixotrophy was then investigated by the mean of RNAseq and transcriptome reconstruction. In mixotrophy we observed down-regulation of genes involved in light harvesting complex, among which the subunit PSBS, putatively involved in Non-Photochemical Quenching of the light absorbed. Downregulation of glycolytic enzymes and upregulation of genes involved in amino acids biosynthesis were linked with increased starch and proteins accumulation in mixotrophy. Acetate assimilation caused upregulation of photorespiratory enzymes producing glyoxylate to be used for acetate derived acetyl-CoA condensation into malate. Moreover, in mixotrophy we observed the upregulation of phosphoenolpyruvate carboxylase enzyme, enabling potential recovery of carbon lost by acetate oxidation. The obtained results allowed to associate the increased productivity observed in mixotrophy in C. sorokiniana with a different gene regulation leading to a change of metabolic pathways.

Moreover, several Chlorella sp. can be cultivated in mixotrophy, adding a reduced carbon substrate as a source of energy in addition to the photosynthetic process. In this work, we investigated the molecular basis of autotrophic vs. mixotrophic growth of Chlorella sorokiniana UTEX1230 strain. In mixotrophic conditions we observed an enhanced biomass, proteins, lipids and starch productivity when compared to autotrophic conditions. Despite decreased chlorophyll and chlorophyll binding protein accumulation, photosynthetic properties were essentially unaffected in C. sorokiniana by acetate addition. Differential gene expression profile in autotrophy as compared to mixotrophy was then investigated by the mean of RNAseq and transcriptome reconstruction. In mixotrophy we observed down-regulation of genes involved in light harvesting complex, among which the subunit PSBS, putatively involved in Non-Photochemical Quenching of the light absorbed. Downregulation of glycolytic enzymes and upregulation of genes involved in amino acids biosynthesis were linked with increased starch and proteins accumulation in mixotrophy. Acetate assimilation caused upregulation of photorespiratory enzymes producing glyoxylate to be used for acetate derived acetyl-CoA condensation into malate. Moreover, in mixotrophy we observed the upregulation of phosphoenolpyruvate carboxylase enzyme, enabling potential recovery of carbon lost by acetate oxidation. The obtained results allowed to associate the increased productivity observed in mixotrophy in C. sorokiniana with a different gene regulation leading to a change of metabolic pathways.

Supplying microalgae with extra CO2 is a promising means for improving lipid production. The molecular mechanisms involved in lipid accumulation under conditions of elevated CO2, however, remain to be fully elucidated. To understand how elevated CO2 improves lipid production, we performed sequencing of Chlorella sorokiniana LS-2 cellular transcripts during growth and compared transcriptional dynamics of genes involved in carbon flow from CO2 to triacylglycerol.

Based on previous studies, this study takes a strain hydrocarbon-producing B. braunii race A (Botryococcus braunii SAG 807-1) as the research object and explores the photosynthetic characteristics of B. braunii under the stress of Co2+. The RNA-seq technique has been used to perform transcriptome sequencing analysis of samples of B. braunii before and after Co2+ stress and explore the metabolic pathways involved in the synthesis of hydrocarbons in algae cells induced by Co2+.

Tisochrysis lutea is a widely used microalgae. This species produces a high-value pigment named fucoxanthin, which has many properties as anti-cancer, anti-ixydant, anti-diabetes. This pigment is of a great interest in pharmacology and aquaculture. In the chloroplasts of Tisochrysis lutea, the fucoxanthin is bound to a protein called FCP. Together, they form the light-harvesting antenna which is a key element in the photosynthesis. We characterized for the first time the FCP in Tisochrysis lutea. As nitrogen and light intensity are two main parameters influencing the photosynthesis, of which the light-harvesting antenna is part, we studied the transcripts level of the 52 genes constituting the FCP while varying these parameters. This works allows to better understand the light-harvesting process in Tisochrysis lutea and to further better anticipate the fucoxanthin production.

Based on previous studies, this study takes a strain hydrocarbon-producing B. braunii race A (Botryococcus braunii SAG 807-1) as the research object and explores the photosynthetic characteristics of B. braunii under the stress of Co2+. The RNA-seq technique has been used to perform transcriptome sequencing analysis of samples of B. braunii before and after Co2+ stress and explore the metabolic pathways involved in the synthesis of hydrocarbons in algae cells induced by Co2+.

Many dinoflagellates species, especially of the Alexandrium genus, produce a series of toxins with tremendous impacts on human and environmental health, as well as economies. We present the full-transcriptome of the dinoflagellate A. tamutum in both control and phosphate starvation conditions. Phosphate starvation was selected because known to induce toxin production for other Alexandrium spp. RNA-seq data were used for in silico identification of transcripts that can be involved in the synthesis of toxic compounds. Results gave new insights on toxic microalgae, toxin production and environmental monitoring.

RNA-seq data of the dinoflagellate Alexandrium catenella under different stress conditions.

Phosphorus (P) is a key macronutrient limiting cell growth and bloom formation of marine dinoflagellates. Physiological responses to changing ambient P have been investigated in dinoflagellates; however, little is known about the molecular mechanisms behind these responses. Here, we compared the transcriptomes of a dinoflagellate Alexandrium catenella grown in inorganic P-replete, P-deficient, and inorganic- and organic P-resupplied conditions using RNA-Seq and characterized differentially expressed genes.

To better understand the mechanisms by which algae respond to light spectrum, we investigated the plasticity of pigment composition and gene expression (i.e., whether pigment composition and expression level changes) in the cryptophyte Rhodomonas salina grown in different spectral environments, expecting that R. salina would respond to maximize their capacity to capture available light. We asked the following questions: 1) How do the concentrations of pigments change in response to different spectral irradiance but equal intensity? and 2) How does gene expression vary among different spectral environments? We examined the pigment and transcriptional responses for the following spectral comparisons: blue vs. red light, green vs. red, and blue vs. green. The blue vs. red light comparison represented the widest energy difference between spectra (as one blue photon is more energetic than one red photon) and reflects distinct habitats in the natural world. Green vs. red light maximized the differences between the expected light absorption of all photosynthetic pigments, where blue vs. green light comparisons represented minimum energetic differences.Our transcriptional responses were investigated at three different scales. First, we examined expression of transcripts that encode the peptide components of cryptophyte phycobiliproteins, predicting that they would correlate with concentration of the pigment and maximize available light capture. Second, we examined expression of 99 genes that were a priori identified as participating in light capture or photosynthesis, predicting that these loci would be most sensitive to light spectrum. Third, we examined genome-wide expression to identify molecular processes that interact with light spectrum but may not have obvious connections to light capture or photosynthesis. We further sought to link our assessment of pigment plasticity (change in pigment composition) and expression plasticity (change in expression level) by testing for correlations between the two across our entire experiment.

The blue vs. red light comparison represented the widest energy difference between spectra (as one blue photon is more energetic than one red photon) and reflects distinct habitats in the natural world. Green vs. red light maximized the differences between the expected light absorption of all photosynthetic pigments, where blue vs. green light comparisons represented minimum energetic differences.Our transcriptional responses were investigated at three different scales. First, we examined expression of transcripts that encode the peptide components of cryptophyte phycobiliproteins, predicting that they would correlate with concentration of the pigment and maximize available light capture. Second, we examined expression of 99 genes that were a priori identified as participating in light capture or photosynthesis, predicting that these loci would be most sensitive to light spectrum. Third, we examined genome-wide expression to identify molecular processes that interact with light spectrum but may not have obvious connections to light capture or photosynthesis. We further sought to link our assessment of pigment plasticity (change in pigment composition) and expression plasticity (change in expression level) by testing for correlations between the two across our entire experiment.

Bryozoans grow by budding new physiologically connected colony members (zooids) from a metamorphosed larva. Zooids are specialized to serve different tasks within the colony such as feeding, reproduction, defense, and colony attachment. This study aims to characterize the differential gene expression between polymorphic zooids of lab-cultured Bugulina stolonifera colonies by sequencing high-quality mRNA from different polymorphic zooid typess at different developmental stages.

To explore the mechanism of triacylglycerol synthesis in Nannochloropsis following nitrogen deprivation.  Nannochloropsis (Eustigmatophyceae) is a genus of unicellular photosynthetic microalgae, ranging in size of 2-5 µm and widely distributed in marine, fresh and brackish waters. They are of industrial interest due to their capability of rapid autotrophic growth, synthesis of large amounts of TAG and polyunsaturated fatty acids (e.g. eicosapentaenoic acid, EPA) that can be readily converted into advanced biofuels and robust outdoor growth with flue gases.

Dinoflagellates represent major contributors to the harmful algal blooms in the oceans. Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient that limits the growth and proliferation of dinoflagellates. However, the specific molecular mechanisms involved in P acclimation of dinoflagellates remain poorly undertood. Here, we compared the transcriptomes of a dinoflagellate Prorocentrum donghaiense grown under inorganic P-replete, P-deficient, and inorganic- and organic P-resupplied conditions.

Here, we compared the transcriptomes of a dinoflagellate Prorocentrum donghaiense grown under inorganic P-replete, P-deficient, and inorganic- and organic P-resupplied conditions.

The responses to osmotic stress in Dunaliella tertiolecta include changes in cell volume, ion transport and varying the production of glycerol. This study sought to identify and characterize new osmolytes that might be present in D. tertiolecta using untargeted metabolomics and RNA-seq.

Certain species of microalgae are natural accumulators of lipids, while others are more inclined to store starch. However, what governs the preference to store lipids or starch is not well understood. In this study, the microalga Dunaliella tertiolecta was used as a model to study the global gene expression profile regulating starch accumulation in microalgae.

we investigated the effect of inputs of CO2 at concentrations of between 1% and 30% on microalgal growth, CO2 fixation rates, and microalgal biomass chemistry using a Dunaliella salina strain under high salt conditions. Transcriptomic analysis was used to investigate the factors affecting microalgal tolerance for high CO2 concentration at a genetic level. These findings extend the knowledge which the key metabolic and biological pathways function in response to extremely high CO2 in marine microalgae.

Plasticity is an important mechanism by which species could persist under fluctuating environments. In this project, we investigated experimentally the evolution of phenotypic plasticity in response to environmental predictability. To do so, we assessed the contribution of the genotype, epigenotype and environment to the phenotypic responses following an environmental change. We also compared the molecular responses (DNA methylation and gene expression) to environmental changes of different evolved populations.

The marine microalga Dunaliella salina (Chlorophyceae) is a phytoplanktonic species that has a great distribution in the marine ecosystems. This species is widely used in laboratory cultures and in toxicity assays to evaluate the effects of industrial effluents. The effects of cadmium exposure on microalgae has been intensively explored previously; however, most of these studies only focused on one or several time end points of the same growth cycle. In the present study, we acclimated the cells to more than three generations, which could be much easier to mimic a natural polluted water environment. In the present study, transcriptome analysis were investigated in control and Cd acclimatization group and reciprocal cadmium change at 6 h and 24 h to identify cadmium specific genes. Our data will help to deepen our understanding of toxicity and adaptation for microalgae in response to cadmium.

Changes in light wavelength can alter the phycobiliprotein content in photosynthetic organisms. These molecules are involved in harvesting light energy for photosynthesis and are interesting microalgal products. Furthermore, increasing or modifying phycobiliprotein content in eucaryotic microalgae is possible. Specifically, exposure to different wavelengths triggers their ability to switch their metabolism using light. Moreover, molecular findings support light modulation of phycobiliproteins in the microalgae Porphyridium cruentum.Therefore, this research aimed to describe how two light spectra affect the transcriptome in P. cruentum cultures.
